job_title: Robotics researcher & engineer | Multi-agent algorithms developer | CS PhD candidate at Harvard
about:
I am a PhD candidate in computer science at Harvard University, where I research autonomous robot collectives. I am interested in developing algorithms for a variety of multi-agent systems, from robots to satellite constellations. I aim to take an interdisciplinary approach to collective robotics, integrating bio-inspiration and mathematical modeling to develop algorithms that can be applied beyond the lab.

I am seeking a research-oriented position in robotics for spring 2022, after the completion of my PhD.

My current research focuses on creating algorithms for distributed decision-making in robot swarms. Specifically, I am developing a modular framework for allowing robots to collectively solve a variety of environmental classification and localization problems. I am also developing collective of low-cost robots capable of moving as aggregate group, inspired by insect larvae.

I consider myself a full-stack roboticist, working on both software (algorithms and control) and hardware (mechanical and electronic design). This lets me consider mechanical and algorithmic co-design in developing robust robot behavior.

For more information, check out my website: juliaebert.com

Currently, she serves as the Assistant Director of Online and Hybrid Programs in the School of Law and is engaged in admissions, advising, and oversees student retention initiatives. She works with graduate cohorts within the Master of Legal Studies, Master of Laws, Media Advocacy degree programs and implements new law certificate programs.

In the past, Marsha was instrumental in making outstanding contributions to the pre-matriculated bridge programs of Global Pathways and American Classroom at the College of Professional Studies. In addition to meeting with and advising ESL, international, undergraduate and adult learners, Marsha helped envision and develop the American Classroom Global Student Ambassadors program, organized and led student orientation events, and served as a liaison to the undergraduate degree programs. Majority of her advisees were placed at Northeastern and nearby colleges.

Marsha is a proud Martin Luther King Fellow and Triple Husky, having received three degrees from Northeastern University. She graduated magna cum laude and received her B.S. in Music Industry, M.A. in Journalism, and M.S. in Nonprofit Management specializing in Higher Education Administration. She is currently enrolled in the Adult and Organizational Learning certificate program at the College of Professional Studies. She continues to hold membership in various affinity groups and professional associations such as the American Association of Blacks in Higher Education and hopes to continue to advance in the field of higher education and earn her EdD.

Scott Frasca’s business experience includes the creation, development, management, leadership and sale of several businesses and has extensive development and outside sales experience. He served in roles as a Congressional liaison and membership consultant for NFIB and NWYC.

He then accepted an opportunity to work on a new Missile Defense System located at Vandenberg AFB. The secret project was ahead of schedule, under budget, and successfully deployed after its first test.

Scott has 30 years of experience in political operations, having worked on multiple campaigns for Governor, President, U.S. Senate, Congress, and many other local and state offices.
